<paragraph blockId="7.[813,1420,794,988]" pageId="7" pageNumber="946">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[813,974,794,818]" pageId="7" pageNumber="946">Identification.</emphasis>
The Margay is a small to medium-sized spotted cat. It may be confused with 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Linnaeus" baseAuthorityYear="1758" box="[1214,1334,829,853]" class="Mammalia" family="Felidae" genus="Leopardus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Carnivora" pageId="7" pageNumber="946" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="pardalis">
<emphasis box="[1214,1334,829,853]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="946">L. pardalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but can be distinguished by its proportionately longer tail (70% of head and body length) and muzzle. 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Schinz" baseAuthorityYear="1821" box="[1231,1420,896,920]" class="Mammalia" family="Felidae" genus="Leopardus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Carnivora" pageId="7" pageNumber="946" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="wiedii">
<emphasis box="[1231,1420,896,920]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="946">Leopardus wiedii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
also has proportionately larger eyes and forefeet, and is largely arboreal (
<bibRefCitation author="Wainwright M &amp; Arias O" box="[998,1305,964,988]" pageId="7" pageNumber="946" refId="ref9590" refString="Wainwright M, Arias O (2007) The mammals of Costa Rica: a natural history and field guide. Comstock, New York, 155 pp." type="book" year="2007">Wainwright and Arias 2007</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
